Our results suggest that higher sensitivity of both short- (higher intra-specific activation energies) and long-term (higher inter-specific activation energies—a HiB constraint) thermal responses in mesophilic prokaryotes may have profound implications for responses of ecosystem fluxes to climatic warming. To illustrate this, we built a simple mathematical model to calculate the potential change in the relative contribution of heterotrophs to ecosystem carbon efflux (based on biomass distributions typical of terrestrial forest ecosystems, see the Methods section). Using our new estimates of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
